# What is an Abstract Class?

## Definition

An **abstract class** is a **blueprint** that **cannot be instantiated (its object cannot be created directly)**. It is used when we want **all child classes 
to follow the same structure** while allowing **each child class to provide its own implementation** for the abstract methods.

## Key Points

* Cannot create an object of an abstract class.
* Used as a blueprint for child classes.
* Ensures all child classes follow the same structure.
* Can contain both **abstract methods** and **concrete (normal) methods**.
* Child classes must implement all abstract methods.

## Example

```python
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod

class Employee(ABC):

    @abstractmethod
    def work(self):
        pass

class Developer(Employee):

    def work(self):
        print("Writing Code")
```
We cannot create an object of an abstract class because it is an incomplete class that serves as a blueprint. Instead, we create objects of its child classes
which provide the implementation for the abstract methods.

